Mau menyimpan 1/1/92

M = 1
D = 1
Y = 92

```1  dalam biner 0000 00000 0000001
1  dalam biner 0000 00000 0000001
92 dalam biner 0000 00000 1011100```

Untuk M,
`0000 00000 0000001`
kita geser ke kiri 12 bit menjadi
`0001 00000 0000000`

Untuk D,
`0000 00000 0000001`
kita geser ke kiri 7 bit menjadi
`0000 00001 0000000`

Untuk Y,
`0000 00000 1011100`
tetap, tidak digeser.

Sehingga hasil akhirnya:
```M = 0001 00000 0000000
D = 0000 00001 0000000
Y = 0000 00000 1011100```

M, D serta Y di-OR kan menjadi
`0001 00001 1011100`
atau bisa kita tulis
`1 00001 1011100`

Hello guys, I would like to ask a question about some code I've written: https://paste.ubuntu.com/p/t59cnMkYvv/\n\nI was trying to write a function to dynamiccaly allocate space in memory, but those two don't really work when I try to use them. They just cause segmentation fault on linux. Could you tell me what I did wrong?
I even stored the return value in a register not to lose it...
I use the linux x64 calling convention

Hi, let me review your code.

Stack is `VM_GROWSDOWN`, meaning that it is a virtual memory that grows downward.

Let see this one
```myMalloc:
        pop     %rdx
        mov     %rsp, %rax
        sub     %rdi, %rsp
        push    %rdx
        ret

```Story in order:
[1] call myMalloc
```RSP -> return address
    -> 

```[2] pop %rdx (rsp will be added by 8)

       -> ~~return address
~~RSP -> 


[3] mov %rsp, %rax
         ->~~ return address
~~RSP, RAX -> 

[4] sub %rdi, %rsp (Let's say the RDI is 16)
RSP -> uninitialized value
    -> uninitialized value (this was return address)
RAX -> 
    -> Previous stack frame


Your return value is a pointer that will clobber previous stack frame if you write 16 bytes to that address.

You should use the uninitialized value below the RAX.

The code should have been like this:

```myMalloc:
        pop     %rdx
        sub     %rdi, %rsp
        mov     %rsp, %rax
        push    %rdx
        ret```

BTW, you should also use `brk()` syscall instead of stack to do something like that.\n\n~~But it looks fine to me for a small program that does not have a production purpose.~~ (No, it is bad, stack frame across function calls will be clobbered).
I just realized, it will still clobber the previous stack frame if you don't restore the stack before other functions which call it, return.
Also, there is a problem when the C compiler uses tail call, pop %rdx will not pop the return address anymore.\n\nSince tail call use `jmp` instead of `call` ðŸ˜‚

what does `fd = -1` mean??\n\nI know that fd means "file descriptor", but I don't understand why "-1"
malam bang kang mba, disini ada yang ngerti mips assembly? bisa bantu sebelumnya abang kaak sekalian?

Basically, we can map a file to memory by using mmap.

This syscall gives us an ability to read/write file content just like read/write to/from memory.

When we write to the file mapped memory, the file content will soon be updated by the kernel.

When we read from the file mapped memory, the content we read will be the content of that mapped file.

It is very good for read/write operation on a big file, physical memory usage will be maintained by the kernel, we just read/write it as memory. It is possible to map a big file, let's say 50 GB file, with machine that only has 4 GB memory.
If we specify the fd = -1, meaning that we don't map a file.
It is also a requirement for `MAP_ANONYMOUS`.

See:
`man 2 mmap`


MAP_ANONYMOUS
The mapping is not backed by any file; its contents are initialized to zero.  The fd argument is ignored; however, some implementations require fd to be -1 if  MAP_ANONYMOUS (or  MAP_ANON)  is  specified, and portable applications should ensure this.  The offset argument should be zero.  The use of MAP_ANONYMOUS in conjunction with MAP_SHARED is supported on Linux only since kernel 2.4.

word*

.data
msg:   .asciiz "Hello World"

        .text
        .globl main
main:   li $v0, 4       # syscall 4 (print_str)
        la $s0, msg     # argument: string
        la $a0, msg     # argument: string
        syscall         # print the string
        la $a0, msg     # argument: string
        jal reversewords
        la $s0, msg     # argument: string
        syscall         # print the string
infiniteloop:
        j infiniteloop  # wait forever
        nop             # branch delay slot

# $a0 holds the address of (the first character of) the string
reversewords:
        addi $sp, $sp, -16  # make room on stack
        sw $ra, 12($sp)     # store regs on stack
        sw $s1, 8($sp)
        sw $s2, 4($sp)
        sw $s3, 0($sp)
        addi $s2, $0, 0
length: add $t4, $a0, $s2
        lb $t3, 0($t4)
        beq $t3, $0, done1
        addi $s2, $s2, 1
        j length
done1:  addi $s1, $s2, 0    # $s1 is the length of the string
        addi $a1, $s1, -1   # $a1 is the offset of the last character
        addi $a2, $0, 0     # $a2 is the offset of the first character
        jal reverse         # call reverse
        addi $t5, $0, 0x20  # $t5 is the ascii code of space,
                            # the character that separates between words
word:   slt $t4, $s1, $s2 # $t4 = 1 if length<i
        bne $t4, $0, return # return if length<i
        beq $s2, $s1, else # if i==length, else
        add $t4, $a0, $s2 # $t4 = &array[i]
        lb $t4, 0($t4) # $t4 = array[i]
        beq $t4, $t5, else # if $t4==0x20,else
        addi $s2, $s2, 1 # i = i + 1
        j word
else:   addi $a1, $s2, -1 # $a1 = i - 1
        addi $a2, $s3, 0 # $a2 = j
        jal reverse
        addi $s2, $s2, 1 # i = i + 1
        addi $s3, $s2, 0 # j = i
        j word


return: lw $ra, 12($sp)     # restore regs
        lw $s1, 8($sp)
        lw $s2, 4($sp)
        lw $s3, 0($sp)
        addi $sp, $sp, 16   # restore $sp
        jr $ra              # return
        
reverse:                    # reverse the string $a0 starting at offset $a1 ending in offset $a2
        slt $t0, $a2, $a1
        beq $t0, $0, exit
        add $t1, $a0, $a1
        lb $t2, 0($t1)
        add $t3, $a0, $a2
        lb $t4, 0($t3)
        sb $t4, 0($t1)
        sb $t2, 0($t3)
        addi $a1, $a1, -1
        addi $a2, $a2, 1
        j reverse
exit:   jr $ra

Klo nentuin clobber itu gmn?\nClobber buat apa sih?

Inline assembly itu bisa mengubah isi register, flag, memory, dll.

Yang jadi masalah kita nggak tahu code yang digenerate compiler akan pakai register apa aja dan compiler nggak tahu inline assembly ngubah register apa aja. Jadi bisa ganggu code generation si compiler. 

Clobber itu tujuannya untuk memberitahu compiler:
"Hey, saya mau ngubah register %rcx dan %r11 di inline assembly ini!".

Dengan begitu si compiler tahu bahwa nilai di %rcx dan %r11 akan berubah, maka kalau si compiler punya nilai penting yang masih kepakai di register itu bakal disimpen dulu nilainya di stack atau di register lain, biar nantinya bisa diload lagi dan nggak hilang.
Disini rax, rdi, rdx, dll nggak perlu di masukan clobber?\nYg buat output aja atau gmn?

Kalau registernya udah masuk ke input/output constraints nggak perlu diclobber.

Note: syscall itu pasti mengubah nilai %rcx dan %r11, plus memory dan %rax kalau ada return value atau internal call `copy_to_user`.

Di situ nggak perlu nambahin rax ke clobber list karena compiler sudah diberi tahu lewat "=a" (artinya kita mau assign nilai ke rax).

#ask apakah kalau bootloader di virtual machine (qemu) berjalan lancar , di real hardware juga nantinya berjalan lancar?

Ga selalu pak.  

There a quite a bit of differences considering that qemu only emulates a real system. So it might happen quite often that code works in qemu
but doesnâ€™t on a real system (or in reverse), especially when directly accessing memory and not using interrupts.
This happened to me quite often when reading from the drive or working with custom interrupt handlers.
Also qemu just boots the image, it doesnâ€™t check if it is in a valid format except if the MBR has the correct signature. dikutip dari https://0x00sec.org/t/realmode-assembly-writing-bootable-stuff-part-3/3116

wah kepanjangan dipake di execve_syscall nya pak.
Wildcard itu fitur shell Pak.\n\nJadi command ls v* itu argumentnya direplace sama shellnya.

Misal di current working directory ada file vaa, vbb, vcc.

Lalu jalankan command ls v* di terminal, si shell bakal replace v* jadi tiga argument vaa vbb vcc.

Jadi sebenernya si ls gak nerima wildcard.

[section .data]
arg0 db "/bin/bash",0
arg1 db "-c",0
arg2 db "ls v*",0
argv dq arg0,arg1,arg2,0

[section .text]
global _start
_start:
xor edx, edx
lea rdi, [rel arg0]
lea rsi, [rel argv]
mov rax,59
syscall
